'''Evonium''' is a purported [[lost city]] in [[Scotland]] first described by [[Hector Boece]] in his 16th-century ''[[Scotorum Historiae]]''. According to Boece, it hosted the coronation of forty kings and was located in the [[Lochaber]] area.<ref name=hector>{{cite book| title=The History of the Scots from Their First Origin| url=http://www.philological.bham.ac.uk/boece/fronteng.html| last=Boece of Dundee| first=Hector| year=1575| accessdate=2014-09-02}}</ref> Boece's translator John Bellenden substituted Dunstaffnage for Evonium which led to the belief that the [[Stone of Scone]] was once kept at [[Dunstaffnage Castle]].<ref name=skene>{{cite book| title=The Coronation Stone| first=William F.| last=Skene| date=7 June 1869| page=14| publisher=Edmonston & Douglas| location=Edinburgh| url=https://archive.org/stream/coronationstone00unkngoog#page/n29/mode/2up| accessdate=2014-09-02}}</ref>
Writer [[A. J. Morton]] has suggested that if Evonium actually existed it could have been located at [[Irvine, North Ayrshire|Irvine]], Ayrshire {{Dubious |Evonium and Irvine |reason=Evonium unlikely to have been located at Irvine |date=October 2013}}, known historically as Erewyn, Ervin or Erevine.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/news/Stone-of-Destiny-39from-Ayrshire.6665396.jp| title=Stone of Destiny 'from Ayrshire, not Perthshire'| last=Cowing| first=Emma| date=19 December 2010| work=[[Scotland on Sunday]]| accessdate=2014-09-02}}</ref>
